d, United Kingdom":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"1140–1207":"1140–1207","1142–1198":"1142–1198","1158–1219":"1158–1219","1187–1246":"1187–1246","1100–1135":"1100–1135","1110–1162":"1110–1162","1187":"1187","1110":"1110","1198":"1198","1142":"1142","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","from 1198 to 1199":"van 1198 to 1199","1246":"1246","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"1140–1207":"1140–1207","1142–1198":"1142–1198","1158–1219":"1158–1219","1187–1246":"1187–1246","1100–1135":"1100–1135","1110–1162":"1110–1162","1187":"1187","1110":"1110","1198":"1198","1142":"1142","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","from 1198 to 1199":"from 1198 to 1199","1246":"1246","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Neville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): habitational name from Neuville in Calvados or Néville in Seine-Maritime, both so called from Old French <i>neu(f)</i> ‘new’ (from Latin <i>novus</i>) + <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’. One family line, originally from Neuville (Calvados), became powerful during the Wars of the Roses through Richard <i>Neville</i> (1428–71), 16th Earl of Warwick, nicknamed \"The Kingmaker\".","Irish (Munster): assimilation of the Gaelic name <b>Ó Niadh</b> (see   Nee  ) and sometimes of <b>Ó Cnaimhín</b> (see   Nevin  ).","History: George Neville came to VA in or <i>c.</i> 1700 and settled on the headwaters of the Occoquan River, acquiring a large estate. His descendants, bearing the surnames Neville and Craig, were of considerable importance in Pittsburgh, PA, and Cincinnati, OH."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevells","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevils","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Novel","meanings":["English: variant of   Neville  .","Catalan: variant of   Novell  ."]},{"name":"Newell","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  .","English: variant of   Noel  .","English: variant of   Newhall  ."]},{"name":"Nevills","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Nevil","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Newill","meanings":["English and Irish (or Norman origin): variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevill","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  ."]},{"name":"Nevels","meanings":["English and Scottish (Wigtownshire): of Norman origin, a variant of   Neville  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Dutch and North German: unexplained."]},{"name":"Nee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Dermot, John Patrick.","Irish (Galway): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Niadh</b> ‘descendant of <i>Nia</i>’ or <b>Mac Niadh</b> ‘son of <i>Nia</i>’. Compare   McNee  .   Needham   2 and   Neville   have also been adopted as Anglicized forms of this name.","North German: possibly a relationship name from Middle Low German <i>neve</i> ‘nephew, grand-child’."]}]},{"name":"Joelin","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Jopelin</i>, a pet form of <i>Jop</i> (see   Job  ) + the double diminutive suffix <i>-elin</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Choplin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Emile, Pierre.","French: diminutive of <b>Chopel</b>, a nickname for someone of unsteady gait, from <i>chopper</i> ‘to knock over’.","Altered form of English   Joplin  ."]},{"name":"Jopling","meanings":["English (Durham and Northumberland): variant of   Joplin  ."]},{"name":"Job","meanings":["Biblical name, pronounced rhyming with ‘robe’. It is borne in the Bible by the hero of the Book of Job, a man of exemplary patience, whose faith was severely tested by God's apparently motiveless maltreatment of him. His name, appropriately enough, means ‘persecuted’ in Hebrew. His story was a favourite one in the Middle Ages and frequently formed the subject of miracle plays. The name was used among Puritans and Christian fundamentalists, but is currently out of favour, although the form  <b>Jobe</b> , presumably a respelling to fix the pronunciation, is occasionally found."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Joelin de Neville clerk in the Exchequer was born in 1140, in Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Jollan de Néville I, was 41 and his mother, Mary FitzRichard, was 30. He had at least 1 son with Amfelicia Rolleston. In 1198, his occupation is listed as justice itenerant in Yorkshire, England. He died in 1207, at the age of 67, and was buried in Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England."},"et":{"1140–1207":"1140–1207","1142–1198":"1142–1198","1158–1219":"1158–1219","1187–1246":"1187–1246","1100–1135":"1100–1135","1110–1162":"1110–1162","1187":"1187","1110":"1110","1198":"1198","1142":"1142","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","from 1198 to 1199":"1198 kuni 1199","1246":"1246","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fi":{"1140–1207":"1140–1207","1142–1198":"1142–1198","1158–1219":"1158–1219","1187–1246":"1187–1246","1100–1135":"1100–1135","1110–1162":"1110–1162","1187":"1187","1110":"1110","1198":"1198","1142":"1142","1130":"1130","1140":"1140","1162":"1162","from 1198 to 1199":"vuodesta 1198 vuoteen 1199","1246":"1246","1158":"1158","1135":"1135","1100":"1100","1208":"1208","1219":"1219","1207":"1207","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England":"Rolleston, Nottinghamshire, England","Rigsby, Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom":"Rigsby, Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England"},"fr":{"1140–1207":"1140–1207","1142–1198":"1142–1198","1158–1219":"1158–1219","1187–1246":"1187–1246","1100–1135":"1100–1135","1110–1162":"1110–1162","1187":"1187","1110":"1110","1198":"11